1. I studied Byteball.{nFirst, I was interested in it. But then I found out that the blockchain (on DAG) is based on witnesses, which are Google and others. Twelve witnesses. No witnesses, no blockchain. I found a video of one of the developers of nByteball giving a lecture. He was very unconvincing about the case. The audience was also, in my opinion, disappointed. Witnesses have to constantly add their transactions to the DAG 24/7. Thereby witnessing the past. If you later add{backslash}transactions with re-spend and parents from the past, there will be no{backslash}witnesses in the way and it will be unusable. The blockchain is written entirely in js. The database is in mysql.To deploy a full client, you have to rent a server, install everything on it, and get a certificate for SSL. The network communication is over https.Although I had the idea of running the client through an anonymous received server.I'm thinking about it.{backslash}n2. Since I still haven't decided on which blockchain principle to stick with, I started looking at {npolkadot. This blockchain is written in Rust. It's a new language. I'm actually a conservative in programming languages, I stuck to C++, and I'm still living it. But I need to understand blockchain, so I downloaded a textbook on Rust, installed a compiler in my house, and am studying it for the third day. It's been claimed that Rust is very suitable for blockchain development. We'll see. If it's really true, if this language improves programmers productivity, then why not. NFT has also come up. We'll have to see. What I've figured out for myself is that we should do the blockchain in DAG. The unit of record in DAG will not be a block with a bunch of transactions, but an individual transaction. A transaction can contain any entity: a coin transfer, a contract, some kind of token (NFT). Mysql as a database, probably. Until I solve the issue{backslash}pc double spending, witnesses. Witnesses can be developers (us), in principle.{nThe first stage without sharding, I think we'll do. For now.
